00:01:56.090 --> 00:01:57.740
against that pretty well.

00:01:57.740 --> 00:02:00.110
But let's be a little bit more
specific in two examples.

00:02:00.110 --> 00:02:03.240
So in Jacob's case, he's talking
about two internet

00:02:03.240 --> 00:02:04.930
radio apps that he has built.

00:02:04.930 --> 00:02:07.730
And in his experience, users
have failed to find the Stop

00:02:07.730 --> 00:02:09.280
button to stop the music.

00:02:09.280 --> 00:02:12.630
Now he's pointed out that in his
particular use case, he's

00:02:12.630 --> 00:02:14.810
not allowed to make the Stop
button more prominent.

00:02:14.810 --> 00:02:17.290
And so this is a genuine
problem.

00:02:17.290 --> 00:02:19.530
So what I would say is, have a
look at the way that Google

00:02:19.530 --> 00:02:21.460
music actually solves this.

00:02:21.460 --> 00:02:24.010
And so really it's about
making sure that Stop--

00:02:24.010 --> 00:02:26.260
stopping the music, stopping
the resource consumption--

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:28.840
is really, really
easy to find.

00:02:28.840 --> 00:02:31.940
So Google music does this by
having the Stop controls along

00:02:31.940 --> 00:02:35.850
the bottom of every activity,
whenever the app is running.

00:02:35.850 --> 00:02:38.770
Or if the app isn't running but
the music is playing, then

00:02:38.770 --> 00:02:41.410
there's an ongoing notification,
which has rich

00:02:41.410 --> 00:02:42.100
notifications.

00:02:42.100 --> 00:02:44.860
Which again allows you
to stop the music.

00:02:44.860 --> 00:02:47.560
And in addition to that, there's
also the lock screen,

00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:50.270
which you can then configure--
and which Google music does--

00:02:50.270 --> 00:02:52.670
to allow you to stop
playback as well.

00:02:52.670 --> 00:02:55.290
And so the solution here,
particularly for music playing

00:02:55.290 --> 00:02:57.950
apps, is that all of those
things I've just described are

00:02:57.950 --> 00:03:00.950
totally available to any
third-party app.

00:03:00.950 --> 00:03:03.210
And so by doing things like
this, it makes it really,

00:03:03.210 --> 00:03:03.920
really easy.

00:03:03.920 --> 00:03:05.510
Even if the Stop button doesn't
have to be half the

00:03:05.510 --> 00:03:08.330
screen, it's just everywhere
they look there's a really

00:03:08.330 --> 00:03:09.530
obvious place to find it.

00:03:09.530 --> 00:03:11.715
And that's going to be much more
reliable than having an

00:03:11.715 --> 00:03:13.570
Exit button, which a
lot of users aren't

00:03:13.570 --> 00:03:17.030
going to find anyway.

00:03:17.030 --> 00:03:19.400
User demands for an Exit button
almost always correlate

00:03:19.400 --> 00:03:21.890
to an app that has confusing
navigation, or hard to find

00:03:21.890 --> 00:03:23.430
controls, or is a
resource hog.

00:03:23.430 --> 00:03:26.150
So adding an Exit button is
going to stop users from

00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:28.930
asking you to add
an Exit button.

00:03:28.930 --> 00:03:32.370
But it's kind of like giving
an aspirin to a patient

00:03:32.370 --> 00:03:35.120
complaining of chronic
abdominal pains.

00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:36.880
They will stop asking
for the painkillers.

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:38.660
But that doesn't actually get
rid of their problem.

00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:41.280
So you're better off trying to
treat the underlying cause

00:03:41.280 --> 00:03:42.850
rather than the symptom.

00:03:42.850 --> 00:03:45.170
And similarly, Daniel [? Drew ?]
asks, how would you

00:03:45.170 --> 00:03:47.560
implement the browser featured
of ditching all cookies on

00:03:47.560 --> 00:03:49.390
exit, if you don't have
an Exit button?

00:03:49.390 --> 00:03:51.680
And that's actually a really
good question.

00:03:51.680 --> 00:03:54.390
In practice I think there's an
assumption that mobile devices

00:03:54.390 --> 00:03:56.780
are inherently more personal
than computers.

00:03:56.780 --> 00:04:01.310
So privacy features like
the removal of

00:04:01.310 --> 00:04:02.740
cookies when you exit--

00:04:02.740 --> 00:04:04.450
which were really designed
around ensuring the

00:04:04.450 --> 00:04:07.440
credentials used by different
users on the same computer--

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:10.780
don't leak, when your wife,
girlfriend, husband, whoever,

00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:12.490
uses your computer.

00:04:12.490 --> 00:04:14.455
So those sorts of features
aren't quite as important for

00:04:14.455 --> 00:04:17.329
a phone, with the implicit
assumption is that there's

00:04:17.329 --> 00:04:19.029
only going to be one
person using it.

00:04:21.860 --> 00:04:24.180
And in fact, it even almost goes
the other way, where the

00:04:24.180 --> 00:04:26.710
pain associated with having to
put in your credentials or

00:04:26.710 --> 00:04:28.840
into the same information
multiple times, is actually

00:04:28.840 --> 00:04:30.890
significantly more annoying
on a phone

00:04:30.890 --> 00:04:31.730
than it is on a computer.

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:35.670
So there's even more reason to
hang on to some of this stuff.

00:04:35.670 --> 00:04:37.850
So that said, if you did want to
do something like that, the

00:04:37.850 --> 00:04:41.440
suggestion I would have is
probably to have a menu

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:44.540
option, probably a settings
option to clear all cookies.

00:04:44.540 --> 00:04:47.230
Or better still, maybe a menu
item, which says something

00:04:47.230 --> 00:04:50.100
like "close all windows and
clear all cookies." Or it just

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:52.370
says "close all windows and
clear all cookies" is one of

00:04:52.370 --> 00:04:54.500
the option that you have.

00:04:54.500 --> 00:04:57.480
So that's answer to two
of those questions.

