00:17:53.500 --> 00:17:59.210
But because we're doing cross
platform, so we want our users

00:17:59.210 --> 00:18:04.140
to know that the device or
application handles the same

00:18:04.140 --> 00:18:06.610
situations all over
the platforms.

00:18:06.610 --> 00:18:09.930
So basically if you have an Exit
button on iPhone, or you

00:18:09.930 --> 00:18:13.910
have an Exit button on Windows,
or on Windows phone

00:18:13.910 --> 00:18:19.600
tablets and so on, or even on
Mac-- you press command Q, you

00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:20.710
exit the app.

00:18:20.710 --> 00:18:25.580
And on Android, the ecosystem is
just, hit the Home button,

00:18:25.580 --> 00:18:29.410
and let Android deal with all
the memory and all the tasks

00:18:29.410 --> 00:18:33.370
ongoing, and so on.

00:18:33.370 --> 00:18:41.560
So what is the best option to
handle the situation for us

00:18:41.560 --> 00:18:48.690
and also give the user the same
atmosphere, or the same

00:18:48.690 --> 00:18:53.750
experience, when moving
from device to device?

00:18:53.750 --> 00:18:58.200
Because basically the user
connects from an iPod, an

00:18:58.200 --> 00:19:05.180
iPhone, an iPad, a Nexus 7,
Nexus 10, Google TV--

00:19:05.180 --> 00:19:07.020
you name the device,
we have it.

00:19:07.020 --> 00:19:11.210
So basically we want the users
to know that [? UVU ?]

00:19:11.210 --> 00:19:13.440
connects people all
over the world.

00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:19.420
No matter what, the same
experience, the same features

00:19:19.420 --> 00:19:22.080
are available on all devices.

00:19:22.080 --> 00:19:25.860
So that's the main issue here.

00:19:25.860 --> 00:19:26.440
RETO MEIER: OK.

00:19:26.440 --> 00:19:27.870
That's a good question.

00:19:27.870 --> 00:19:29.960
And it's actually an
interesting one.

00:19:29.960 --> 00:19:34.120
Because I hear this a lot from
developers who are building

00:19:34.120 --> 00:19:36.820
these cross platform solutions,
where they want to

00:19:36.820 --> 00:19:38.940
have something really consistent
across all the

00:19:38.940 --> 00:19:39.930
different devices.

00:19:39.930 --> 00:19:43.026
Now the thing is, there's sort
of two different ways that I

00:19:43.026 --> 00:19:43.700
would approach this.

00:19:43.700 --> 00:19:47.360
And the first is that it's
actually fairly unlikely that

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:49.820
you're going to have a
significant number of users

00:19:49.820 --> 00:19:53.190
which have multiple different
devices from different

00:19:53.190 --> 00:19:54.680
manufacturers.

00:19:54.680 --> 00:19:57.926
So you're not going to have a
lot of people which have an

00:19:57.926 --> 00:19:59.970
IPhone and an Android phone.

00:19:59.970 --> 00:20:02.090
There will be some--

00:20:02.090 --> 00:20:05.210
and this leads me to my second
point, which is that people

00:20:05.210 --> 00:20:07.826
expect their devices to
behave consistently.

00:20:07.826 --> 00:20:10.210
They don't necessarily expect
apps to work exactly the same

00:20:10.210 --> 00:20:11.560
across different devices.

00:20:11.560 --> 00:20:15.450
So if I've got an iPad, then I
expect all of the apps to work

00:20:15.450 --> 00:20:17.370
in a way that's consistent with
the way all of the other

00:20:17.370 --> 00:20:18.390
iPad apps work.

00:20:18.390 --> 00:20:20.455
And if I have Android,
then I expect them to

00:20:20.455 --> 00:20:21.460
all work with Android.

00:20:21.460 --> 00:20:26.330
So what you don't have is an
iPhone user expecting their

00:20:26.330 --> 00:20:29.030
Android phone to work in the
same way as their iPhone.

00:20:29.030 --> 00:20:31.790
Because it's a different
device, right?

00:20:31.790 --> 00:20:33.410
They don't have the
same expectations.

00:20:33.410 --> 00:20:36.310
If they did, they get really
confused when they started

00:20:36.310 --> 00:20:39.850
using things like Mail and Maps
and Music and Twitter and

00:20:39.850 --> 00:20:40.440
everything else.

00:20:40.440 --> 00:20:42.350
Because they just inherently
behave differently.

00:20:42.350 --> 00:20:43.960
And it's the same
with computers.

00:20:43.960 --> 00:20:46.030
You expect your computer to
work in a certain way.

00:20:46.030 --> 00:20:51.260
Expect to have that command Q
to get out of an app in Mac.

00:20:51.260 --> 00:20:52.460
If you've got Windows,
you expect to

00:20:52.460 --> 00:20:54.180
be able to hit Alt-F4.

00:20:54.180 --> 00:20:57.270
But what you're not
expecting is--

00:20:57.270 --> 00:21:00.290
a good example is, if you're
building an app for both

00:21:00.290 --> 00:21:04.230
Windows and Mac, you're not
going to build the command Q

00:21:04.230 --> 00:21:06.330
shortcut into the Windows app.

00:21:06.330 --> 00:21:08.270
So that people who are
using it on Mac

00:21:08.270 --> 00:21:09.520
understand how to quit.

00:21:09.520 --> 00:21:12.565
You're going to build in the
same user patterns that

00:21:12.565 --> 00:21:14.160
they're expecting for Windows.

00:21:14.160 --> 00:21:15.420
And it's the same
across mobile.

00:21:15.420 --> 00:21:19.200
Like, I wouldn't tell you to
build your iPhone apps so that

00:21:19.200 --> 00:21:21.900
they work and look the same
as your Android apps.

00:21:21.900 --> 00:21:24.560
You want to have a consistent
experience between the

00:21:24.560 --> 00:21:26.680
platform because that's
what they're doing

00:21:26.680 --> 00:21:28.610
within a given context.

00:21:28.610 --> 00:21:32.010
So for your app in particular,
what you want to do, what your

00:21:32.010 --> 00:21:34.990
users are going to expect is
that if you're signed in but

00:21:34.990 --> 00:21:37.030
your app is not in the
foreground, then it shouldn't

00:21:37.030 --> 00:21:38.880
be consuming any resources.

00:21:38.880 --> 00:21:40.710
And that's just going to
be their expectation.

00:21:40.710 --> 00:21:43.250
Some may look to find
an Exit button.

00:21:43.250 --> 00:21:44.840
But if you're not doing
anything, if you're not

00:21:44.840 --> 00:21:47.380
consuming any resources, if the
phone's not going slower,

00:21:47.380 --> 00:21:49.570
if you're not doing background
polling, you're not waking up

00:21:49.570 --> 00:21:50.370
the phone--

00:21:50.370 --> 00:21:51.980
you're just receiving
those updates using

00:21:51.980 --> 00:21:53.470
Google Cloud Messaging.

00:21:53.470 --> 00:21:55.030
Then they're going
to be happy.

00:21:55.030 --> 00:21:56.660
They're not going to be looking
for something if

00:21:56.660 --> 00:21:58.770
there's no reason
to look for it.

00:21:58.770 --> 00:22:00.560
So that would be my big
piece of advice.

00:22:00.560 --> 00:22:04.460
Don't try to over simplify
across devices.

00:22:04.460 --> 00:22:07.390
Because in my experience
that tends to be what

00:22:07.390 --> 00:22:09.130
bosses, what CEOs do.

00:22:09.130 --> 00:22:11.270
They look at all of your apps
across all the different

00:22:11.270 --> 00:22:12.210
phones

00:22:12.210 --> 00:22:14.565
AUDIENCE: That's
our issue here.

00:22:14.565 --> 00:22:20.090
The designers or product guys
basically want the same

00:22:20.090 --> 00:22:22.370
features to be on all devices.

00:22:22.370 --> 00:22:26.860
And my main concern or my main
issue as an Android developer

00:22:26.860 --> 00:22:31.810
is to show them the Android
system is not the same as the

00:22:31.810 --> 00:22:32.770
iOS system.

00:22:32.770 --> 00:22:33.930
Or is not the same--

00:22:33.930 --> 00:22:37.220
so you have the basic
conventions in Android, such

00:22:37.220 --> 00:22:42.540
as the Home key or not showing
the exit option.

00:22:42.540 --> 00:22:45.540
I agree that you don't need
an Exit button on your

00:22:45.540 --> 00:22:46.810
application.

00:22:46.810 --> 00:22:52.410
