00:31:07.870 --> 00:31:11.230
Particularly phone users who
don't really think of their

00:31:11.230 --> 00:31:13.890
phone as being a computer
that runs apps.

00:31:13.890 --> 00:31:15.460
They just think of it
as a device that

00:31:15.460 --> 00:31:17.120
lets them do stuff.

00:31:17.120 --> 00:31:19.190
I mean, I remember reading
a survey--

00:31:19.190 --> 00:31:21.110
I think it was late last year
or early this year--

00:31:21.110 --> 00:31:24.210
which asked people, do you use
the internet on your phone?

00:31:24.210 --> 00:31:28.870
And most said, no, I don't use
the internet on my phone.

00:31:28.870 --> 00:31:31.330
And the follow-up question
is like, well, do

00:31:31.330 --> 00:31:32.790
you check your email?

00:31:32.790 --> 00:31:34.180
Do you update Facebook?

00:31:34.180 --> 00:31:34.750
Do you use Twitter?

00:31:34.750 --> 00:31:36.270
And they're like, yeah,
definitely do

00:31:36.270 --> 00:31:37.490
all of those things.

00:31:37.490 --> 00:31:39.010
And it's like--

00:31:39.010 --> 00:31:41.710
the internet, how
does it work?

00:31:41.710 --> 00:31:43.450
That's what's making all
of these things work.

00:31:43.450 --> 00:31:44.700
But people don't think
of it that way.

00:31:48.090 --> 00:31:50.640
All of the implementation
details about how these apps

00:31:50.640 --> 00:31:52.250
work-- the fact that there
are apps running in a

00:31:52.250 --> 00:31:55.010
multi-tasking operating system
connecting to the internet

00:31:55.010 --> 00:31:59.440
over ethernet or a cell network,
TCP/IP connection.

00:31:59.440 --> 00:32:00.130
They don't know any of that.

00:32:00.130 --> 00:32:01.440
They don't care about
any of that.

00:32:01.440 --> 00:32:03.760
They just want to do something,
like order a taxi,

00:32:03.760 --> 00:32:05.080
or check their email, or update

00:32:05.080 --> 00:32:06.800
Twitter, or take a photo.

00:32:06.800 --> 00:32:09.310
And how it all works means
nothing to them.

00:32:09.310 --> 00:32:12.460
And so in that context, Exit
doesn't make any sense.

00:32:12.460 --> 00:32:14.560
Like, I just want to
update Twitter.

00:32:14.560 --> 00:32:15.880
And then I want to
take a photo.

00:32:15.880 --> 00:32:17.970
I don't want to have to think
about exiting one app to start

00:32:17.970 --> 00:32:19.250
up another.

00:32:19.250 --> 00:32:20.780
So it's really about changing
those paradigms.

00:32:20.780 --> 00:32:24.980
And getting people thinking
in a different way.

00:32:24.980 --> 00:32:26.980
I mean, you can say anything
is old school.

00:32:26.980 --> 00:32:31.310
Like, I remember when I was in
high school thinking, I can't

00:32:31.310 --> 00:32:31.670
believe it.

00:32:31.670 --> 00:32:33.960
This new computer I'm going
to buy doesn't have a 5

00:32:33.960 --> 00:32:35.160
and 1/4 inch disk.

00:32:35.160 --> 00:32:36.490
That's ridiculous.

00:32:36.490 --> 00:32:38.980
I mean I know I mainly use the
3 and 1/2 inch floppies now.

00:32:38.980 --> 00:32:41.390
But the 5 and 1/4 is
never going away.

00:32:41.390 --> 00:32:42.700
Yeah, it went away.

00:32:42.700 --> 00:32:45.430
And then the 3 and 1/2 inch went
away not too long enough

00:32:45.430 --> 00:32:46.130
afterwards.

00:32:46.130 --> 00:32:49.810
And then hard drives started
to end up in the terabytes.

00:32:49.810 --> 00:32:52.070
My point is that
things change.

00:32:52.070 --> 00:32:54.770
And I think as developers,
we need to adapt to that.

00:32:54.770 --> 00:32:56.830
And the trend is really to try
and make things easier and

00:32:56.830 --> 00:32:58.860
easier for users, so they don't
have to think about how

00:32:58.860 --> 00:33:00.210
do I use a computer?

